english:
  title: The Ode to Plum Stream
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the year of Gengsheng,
    as winter deepens toward its close,
    the air bites like a blade.
    Bare trees cry out in the wind.

    Three-Peak Wanderer laces his wooden clogs
    and steps beyond the gate.
    All around, a desolate expanse—
    the world wrapped in shadow and chill.

    Then, sudden as a whisper at the tip of my nose,
    a pure fragrance.
    Touch it—it vanishes.
    Seek it—there is nowhere to find it.
    Dazed, not knowing what it might be,
    my heart aches with longing.

    Then the night snow melts away,
    and moonlight flows clear and bright.
    I wade the shallow stream,
    wandering lost in contemplation,
    when suddenly, radiant beside the water,
    I find her.

    Who are you? I cannot speak.
    Yet in that innocent grace,
    that composed countenance—
    white robes, white sleeves,
    feathered garments like rainbow silk,
    snow-white skin luminous and supple,
    a face of jade, light and graceful,
    fluttering as though crossing the silver river,
    passing through the Palace of Vast Cold,
    encountering all the immortals in the highest heaven.

    A young voice speaks, half-teasing:
    "All things gather with their kind.
    The celestial and mortal dwell apart.
    The clear and turbid do not mingle.
    Of all things, snow is most pristine.
    Of all essences, moonlight is most luminous.
    Above and below, seamless,
    a single, crystalline radiance.
    Thus the Creator fulfills my joy,
    and by this I am truly content.

    Why concern myself with the human world?
    What are a few lifetimes of dust?
    The fever of mankind
    cannot afflict me.
    The chains of convention
    cannot bend my truth.

    But tell me—who are you, and from where do you come?"

    Three-Peak Wanderer startled,
    his hair bristling with wonder.
    He rubbed his eyes and looked again—
    only to see that he himself walked
    with Hao-fu through Plum Stream.
  footnotes:
    - Gengsheng (庚申) refers to a specific year in the East Asian sexagenary cycle, suggesting this is a dated composition.
    - Three-Peak Wanderer (三峯子) is Jeong Do-jeon's own literary pseudonym, making this a work of subtle self-reflection.
    - The Palace of Vast Cold (廣寒殿) is the mythical palace of the Moon Goddess in Chinese and East Asian tradition.
    - Hao-fu (浩甫) is likely a companion or perhaps represents another aspect of the poet's contemplation, making the ending deliberately ambiguous about the nature of what has been encountered.
